6–Deceased","1452–1521":"1452–1521","1456–1521":"1456–1521","17 June 1521":"17 June 1521","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1567":"1567","1501":"1501","1555":"1555","1456":"1456","1521":"1521","1477":"1477","1452":"1452","1485":"1485","1508":"1508","1559":"1559","1526":"1526","Chicester, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Wotton-under-Edge, Stroud, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Wotton under Edge, Gloucestershire, England","Chichester, Sussex, England":"Chichester, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England","Edge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Edge, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Upton Snodsbury, Sussex, England":"Upton, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Millard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Millward  .","French and German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>mil</i> ‘good, gracious’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. Compare   Milord  .","French (southern): from a variant of Occitan <i>milhar</i> ‘millet field’, a derivative of <i>mil</i> ‘millet’."],"variants":[{"name":"Milliard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Guillaume, Treffle.","French: variant of   Millard  .","English (southern, especially Bedfordshire): variant of   Millward  ."]},{"name":"Millward","meanings":["English (mainly West Midlands): occupational name from Middle English <i>milne-ward</i>, <i>mille-ward</i> ‘keeper of a mill, miller’ (Old English <i>mylen-weard</i>). In southern England and the West Midlands this was a standard medieval term for a miller. Compare   Miller  ."]},{"name":"Milord","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Francois, Herve, Marie Carmel, Veronique.  Spanish Berta, Lorenza, Narciso, Tulia.","French and Haitian: nickname for an important or rich man, from <i>milord</i>, a borrowing of English <i>my lord</i>. Or, in Haiti, from the personal name <i>Milord</i> of the same origin. This surname was brought to the US mostly from Haiti, where it is by far most common.","Altered form of French   Millard   2."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Millard was born in 1470, in Chichester, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, his father, Richard Phillpott Alias Milward, was 18 and his mother, Cateryne Philpott, was 14. He had at least 1 son with Eleanor Rogers. He died in 1559, in Upton, Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 89."},"et":{"1470–1559":"1470–1559","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","1501–1560":"1501–1560","1508–Male":"1508–Surnud","1470–1555":"1470–1555","1490–1567":"1490–1567","1526–Male":"1526–Surnud","1452–1521":"1452–1521","1456–1521":"1456–1521","17 June 1521":"17. juuni 1521","1560":"1560","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1567":"1567","1501":"1501","1555":"1555","1456":"1456","1521":"1521","1477":"1477","1452":"1452","1485"